{"id": "26286", "post": "<div class=\"post-26286 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-editorial tag-security tag-sudo\" id=\"post-26286\"><h2 class=\"storytitle\"><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/huge-sudo-security-issue-update-your-systems-now/\" rel=\"bookmark\">Huge sudo Security Issue \u2013 Update Your Systems Now!</a></h2><div class=\"meta\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" data-src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" alt=\"Tags: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/security/\" rel=\"tag\">Security</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/sudo/\" rel=\"tag\">sudo</a> <img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" alt=\"Date/Time: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> January 27, 2021 @ 12:37 am, by raindog308</div><div class=\"storycontent tablelook\"><p><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/sandwich.png.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"size-full wp-image-26287 alignright litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/sandwich.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"249\" align=\"right\" hspace=\"20\" data-was-processed=\"true\"><a href=\"https://www.sudo.ws/alerts/unescape_overflow.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">News broke today</a> of a new security vulnerability in <strong>sudo</strong>, a widely used Linux/BSD/Unix utility that allows regular users to execute commands with elevated privileges.</p><p>Typically, a user may need elevated (root) privileges to perform some command on the system, so the system administrator configures sudo to allow that user the ability to run one (or a set) of commands.&nbsp; If you are not listed in the /etc/sudoers file, you have no access to sudo, and if you are, you have access only to commands you\u2019ve been permitted to use.</p><p>The new vulnerability means that&nbsp;<em>any</em> user can elevate his privileges to root using a carefully crafted arguments to one of sudo\u2019s programs (sudoedit) \u2013 even if the user is not listed in /etc/sudoers!</p><p>If you\u2019re the only user on your system (i.e., a personal VPS) you are probably not immediately affected because the user must be logged in with a shell to use sudo.&nbsp; However, you should still update.&nbsp; If you run a system where you have many users and use sudo, you must update immediately (to version 1.9.5p2).</p><p>(As is often the case, the only major Unix-like OS that is not affected is OpenBSD, which ditched sudo in favor of its homegrown utility, <a href=\"https://man.openbsd.org/doas\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">doas</a>, <a href=\"https://www.vultr.com/docs/introduction-to-doas-on-openbsd\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">back in 2015</a> due to security concerns with sudo.)</p><div class=\"relpost-thumb-wrapper\"><div class=\"relpost-thumb-container\"><h3>Related posts:</h3><div style=\"clear: both\"></div><div style=\"clear: both\"></div><div class=\"relpost-block-container\"><a class=\"relpost-block-single\" href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/how-to-keep-your-wordpress-site-secure/\"><div style=\"width: 150px; height: 215px;\"><div class=\"relpost-block-single-image\" alt=\"How to Keep your WordPress Site Secure\" style=\"background: transparent url(https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-to-keep-your-wordpress-site-secure-150x150.jpg) no-repeat scroll 0% 0%; width: 150px; height: 150px;\"></div><div class=\"relpost-block-single-text\" style=\"font-family: Arial;  font-size: 12px;  color: #333333;\">How to Keep Your WordPress Site Secure</div></div></a><a class=\"relpost-block-single\" href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/lowendprotection-homemade-raspberry-pi-security-cloud-camera-setup/\"><div style=\"width: 150px; height: 215px;\"><div class=\"relpost-block-single-image\" 